@ajs2 I was about to recommend a simple ethernet cable for cost.

But if @prensing is concerned with the repeated bending potentially causing a stress-break in the wire, ethernet is usually solid wire which is more susceptible to this work hardening failure mode. Although its smaller so it handles it longer than larger gauges.

@prensing where exactly in the chain did the wire break? Could it have had tension on it when things move? What wire gauge is it? If it was fairly small work hardening takes longer to be problematic like @sokoloff elludes too, needing many many cycles to cause a wire failure due to work-hardening alone.
